User Account Forensics (Research Notes)
	•	Focus: tracking user activity, authentication, and account changes across local + domain environments
	•	Accounts = primary attack surface → used for:
	•	unauthorized access
	•	privilege escalation
	•	persistence

⸻

Types of Accounts (observations)
	•	Local accounts
	•	only exist on one machine
	•	stored in SAM
	•	weak management → common misconfigs
	•	Domain accounts
	•	managed by Domain Controller
	•	stored in NTDS.dit
	•	can access multiple systems
	•	compromise = high impact
	•	System / Service accounts
	•	used by OS/services
	•	often high privilege
	•	misconfig → easy escalation

⸻

Key Artefacts I should always check

⸻

1. Event Logs (primary evidence)

GUI Path:

Event Viewer → Windows Logs → Security

File Path:

C:\Windows\System32\winevt\Logs\Security.evtx

Important Event IDs:
	•	4720 → account created
	•	4722 → account enabled
	•	4738 → account modified
	•	4726 → account deleted
	•	4740 → account locked
	•	4624 → successful logon
	•	4625 → failed logon

Gives:
	•	username + domain
	•	SID
	•	source of action
	•	timestamps

⸻

2. SAM (Local Accounts)

Path:

C:\Windows\System32\Config\SAM

Related hive (needed):

C:\Windows\System32\Config\SYSTEM

Contains:
	•	local usernames + SIDs
	•	password hashes
	•	account status
	•	last login

Used for:
	•	offline analysis
	•	local compromise investigation

⸻

3. NTDS.dit (Domain Accounts)

Path (on Domain Controller):

C:\Windows\NTDS\NTDS.dit

Required for decryption:

C:\Windows\System32\Config\SYSTEM

Export location (example from lab):

C:\Exports\Active Directory\NTDS.dit
C:\Exports\registry\SYSTEM

Contains:
	•	domain users
	•	NTLM password hashes
	•	group memberships
	•	login timestamps
	•	account status

Used for:
	•	domain compromise
	•	credential extraction
	•	lateral movement analysis

⸻

4. Registry Artefacts

Key paths:

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM
HKEY_CURRENT_USER
HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies

Security database:

C:\Windows\security\database\secedit.sdb

Used for:
	•	user rights assignments
	•	policy changes
	•	system/service configs

⸻

5. GPO Artefacts (Domain)

SYSVOL Path:

C:\Windows\SYSVOL\sysvol\

Scripts location (example):

C:\Windows\SYSVOL\sysvol\<domain>\Policies\<GPO_ID>\User\Scripts\Logon

Registry paths affected:

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies
HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM

Network config files:

C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc

Things to check:
	•	login scripts
	•	disabled firewall
	•	modified user rights

⸻

Tools I would use
	•	Event Viewer → view logs
	•	PowerShell
	•	Get-LocalUser
	•	Get-ADUser
	•	DSInternals → extract NTDS.dit data
	•	ntdsutil → export NTDS + SYSTEM hive
	•	Registry Explorer → analyse SAM/registry
	•	Autopsy / FTK → full forensic analysis
	•	Wireshark → analyse NTLM/Kerberos traffic
	•	Volatility → memory artefacts

⸻

Key understanding
	•	SAM → local accounts
	•	NTDS.dit → domain accounts
	•	Event logs → timeline
	•	Registry → supporting evidence
	•	GPO → persistence + lateral movement

⸻

Important takeaway
	•	local account compromise → limited impact
	•	domain account compromise → large impact
	•	domain controller compromise → full network takeover

⸻

Overall idea

User account forensics = correlating:
	•	logs
	•	account databases (SAM / NTDS)
	•	registry
	•	GPO artefacts

to answer:
	•	who did what
	•	when it happened
	•	how access was achieved

